So, in the books of the thirteenth century ¹, the man who has been injured, and who is going to bring an appetu, must in the first place raise hue and cry, and go to the neighbouring townships and declare the crime; and in the later books the appellor is always made to say that he at once made suit to the four neighbouring townships². It may be thus that the four townships became a second body oi witnesses which could traverse the testimony of the hundred-jury. At any rate, in the roll before us, in case the twelve jurors think a rnan guilty, it seems the regular practice to take the opinion oi three or four vills³, or oi the jurors from another hundred ⁴.
